04574nam a22006135i 9780271077499DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710774997 a10.1515/97802710774992doi  a(DE-B1597)583928  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0150802bisacsh04a709.02/42231 aD'Elia, Una Roman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRaphael's Ostrich /cUna Roman D'Elia. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b70 color/130 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Raphael's Disputed Legacy -- t1 A Brief History of the Ostrich: Antiquity and the Middle Ages -- t2 The Eagle and the Ostrich: The Court of Urbino -- t3 Pope Leo X and Raphael's Ostriches -- t4 Raphael' s Heirs -- t5 Farnese Ostriches and Vasari' s Raphael -- t6 Fortune Is an Ostrich: Discontent in the 1550s and 1560s -- t7 Curiosity and the Ostrich in the Counter -Reformation -- t8 Taming the Ostrich: Ripa and Aldrovandi -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRaphael's Ostrich begins with a little-studied aspect of Raphael's painting-the ostrich, which appears as an attribute of Justice, painted in the Sala di Costantino in the Vatican. Una Roman D'Elia traces the cultural and artistic history of the ostrich from its appearances in ancient Egyptian hieroglyphs to the menageries and grotesque ornaments of sixteenth-century Italy. Following the complex history of shifting interpretations given to the ostrich in scientific, literary, religious, poetic, and satirical texts and images, D'Elia demonstrates the rich variety of ways in which people made sense of this living "monster," which was depicted as the embodiment of heresy, stupidity, perseverance, justice, fortune, gluttony, and other virtues and vices. Because Raphael was revered as a god of art, artists imitated and competed with his ostrich, while religious and cultural critics complained about the potential for misinterpreting such obscure imagery. This book not only considers the history of the ostrich but also explores how Raphael's painting forced viewers to question how meaning is attributed to the natural world, a debate of central importance in early modern Europe at a time when the disciplines of modern art history and natural history were developing. The strangeness of Raphael's ostrich, situated at the crossroads of art, religion, myth, and natural history, both reveals lesser-known sides of Raphael's painting and illuminates major cultural shifts in attitudes toward nature and images in the Renaissance. More than simply an examination of a single artist or a single subject, Raphael's Ostrich offers an accessible, erudite, and charming alternative to Vasari's pervasive model of the history of sixteenth-century Italian art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271077499zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271077499423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271077499/original  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK